                    <div3>
                        <head>
                            <title type="section">
                                <hi rend="i">Minute Particulars</hi>
                            </title>
                        </head>
                        <p>Mr. Leslie Parris of the Tate Gallery sends us a copy of “Blake’s Last Picture,”
a hitherto unnoticed poem by George Powell Thomas (<hi rend="i">Poems</hi>, London, 1847). According to a
footnote by the author, the poem is based on a passage in Allan Cunningham’s <hi rend="i">Lives of the
Painters.</hi> The poem is some 100 lines long and, as Mr. Parris says, “a feeble effort.” Thomas was,
according to his title page, a Captain in the Bengal Army and author of <hi rend="i">Views of Simla.</hi> “So
far as I know,” Mr. Parris writes, “he was no relative of the Joseph Thomas I’ve been working on
recently.”</p>
                    </div3>
                </div2>
